	   <tr><td colspan=2>Actually, the assumption that an entire packet would be sent just to submit a signed character is false.<br><br>And to help you further... 256 bits of information would generate a number greater than the number of atoms in the universe.<br><br>What you were looking for is 8 bits of information... 8 bits generates a number between 0 and 255 (256 total numbers) unless you use one bit for the sign (+/-) in which case you have 7 bits which can give you a number between 0 and 127 (128 total numbers).<br><br>And it has nothing to do with packets, other than a character (8bits) was used to store the data instead of a word (16bits) or double-word (32bits).<br><br>&quot;It is better to have people think you're an idiot than open your mouth and remove all doubt.&quot;<br>- Mark Twain, if memory serves, was credited with this saying... smart guy<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
